Here's the recommended approach using `Window` lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**1. Create a custom `Window` subclass** that saves/restores your draft:

```csharp
// AppWindow.cs
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        if (Page is AppShell shell && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        if (Page is AppShell shell && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            note.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        if (Page is AppShell shell && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }
}
```

**2. Return it from `App.CreateWindow`:**

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`OnStopped`** â€” fires when the app is fully backgrounded; save here.
- **`OnResumed`** â€” fires when returning from background; restore here.
- **`OnDestroying`** â€” also save here because Android's back button can skip `Stopped`.
- **`Preferences`** is ideal for small text â€” it's fast and synchronous, avoiding ANR/watchdog kills (keep handlers under 1â€“2 seconds).
- **`OnResumed` does NOT fire on first launch** â€” the initial sequence is `Created â†’ Activated`, so load any persisted draft in your page's constructor or `OnAppearing` instead.
